<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#F0DCA0">Originally posted by rat on 12-18-1999 09:47 PM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=20 COLS=75 WRAP="VIRTUAL">Well, most of what you describe would totally rule, but I'm afraid the CPU power for that kind of tricks just isn't here yet.  Computing the 3D shadows requires a lot of raytracing, which eats CPU like nothing, and because of this it has to be done at a low resolution.  So what you get if you dance around a pillar is a cone of shadow, but only the rough outline of it.  To perfectly match the silhouette of the pillar on the ground, darkening exactly the right pixels, would be much too slow (ask anyone who used POVRay  ;) (*))  So you get the right effect but at a low resolution, which means it's a bit blocky.  Also for this reason we're not doing much with the sun and clouds, so during the day not much happens outside.  During the night however trees, rocks etc all cast the same style of 3D shadows if any light appears nearby (be it from a walking character with a torch, or a magic fireball whizzing by).  In theory it works everywhere but the editors may have to cool it a bit if they build rooms chokefull of architecture, furniture, decoration and what not  ;)
So to wrap it up, there's 3D shadows inside, everywhere, and outside during the night.  The 3D shadows work for any moving light, including character lights or magical lights.  Shadows obviously only occur where there's light, so if these lightsources change (shrink/expand or change color) the shadows would change along...

(*) Also, remember the game is using 2D sprites.  Any 3D effect at all has to be a hack by definition, since I don't have any mesh files.  That's also a reason the shadows don't rotate with the sun : if the sun is exactly in the east or west the shadow would clearly show the characters are totally flat in 3D  ;)  ;)  That would suck.</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
